06725nam a22008535i 9781474488877DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744888777 a10.1515/97814744888772doi  a(DE-B1597)625032  a(OCoLC)1346096001  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a230.090422304aThe Edinburgh Critical History of Twentieth-Century Christian Theology /ced. by Philip Ziegler. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Edinburgh Critical History of Christian Theology : ECHCT00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNotes on Contributors -- tEditor’s Introduction -- t1 Modern Theology in a Scientific, Historical Age -- t2 Tradition and Innovation -- t3 Scripture and Criticism -- t4 Reason, Method, System -- t5 Catholicism and Ecumenism -- t6 Fundamentalism and Evangelicalism -- t7 Synagogue, Sho’ah and State -- t8 Religion(s) -- t9 God -- t10 Spirit -- t11 Christ -- t12 Liberation and Freedom -- t13 The Secular – The Political: Augustine and Political Augustinianism in Twentieth-Century Political Theology -- t14 Globalisation after Empires: World Christianity and the Theological De-centring of Europe -- t15 War and Peace -- t16 Race and Black Theology -- t17 Sex and Gender -- t18 Hope -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn innovative conceptual survey of Christian theology in the twentieth century in relation to key historical events and transformative developments in intellectual and ecclesial cultures. This volume re-examines the history of twentieth-century Christian theology by tracing key concepts, problems and themes as they develop in context with new perspectives opened up by contemporary theology itself. The ambition is to illuminate the context, dynamism and complexities of its traditions and in doing so to offer a critical and creative ressourcement for contemporary theologians. The range of international contributors to this volume inquire afresh into the preoccupations, problems, provocations and prospects of Christian theology in the century just past to ask anew about just what in this recent history matters and why. Key features: A distinctive mapping of twentieth-century theology organized around crucial concepts rather than as a story of ‘great thinkers’ A variegated account which is alert to the continuing formative interaction of theology with philosophy and wider scientific culture, as well as to the social and political changes which reshaped the context within which theology was done Contributors include Elina Vuola, Rachel Muers, Jane Barter Moulaison, Mark Lindsay and Travis Kroeker.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aTheologyxHistoryy20th century. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh1 aAtherstone, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarter, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBateza, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastelo, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChalamet, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrumett, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHedges, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmer, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Kirsteen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKroeker, P. Travis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator